<CaseStudy
  title="Redesigning a product development lifecycle"
  eyebrow="Branch · 2025–2026"
  summary="Architecting a four-phase operating model with named DACI ownership, paired problem and technical briefs, mandatory success metrics before Build, and post-launch decision loops. Adopted across product, design, engineering, and PMM."
  role="Sr. Director of Product Experience"
  duration="Multi-quarter rollout"
  team="Product, Design, Engineering, PMM, Marketing"
  outcome="Operating model adopted org-wide"
>
  <h2>The problem we kept paying for</h2>

  <p>
    The company was shipping product, but Define was a black hole. Problems got framed by
    PM alone, designers entered the work at ticket assignment instead of at problem framing,
    engineers reacted to scoped solutions instead of shaping them, and analytics arrived
    after launch instead of before. The cost of this wasn't just velocity. It was that
    teams kept shipping features without success metrics, and those features quietly
    accumulated into a heavier and heavier system.
  </p>

  <p>
    The biggest tell was the gap between launch and measurement. Almost nothing that
    shipped had a dashboard plan defined before Build started. So we couldn't tell which
    features were working. So we couldn't make Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decisions.
    So nothing got deprecated. So the system got heavier every quarter.
  </p>

  <p>
    I was asked to lead the redesign of how the company builds product. Not a process
    document. A real operating model that product, design, engineering, and PMM would
    actually adopt.
  </p>

  <h2>The four-phase model</h2>

  <p>
    The framework I built moves every initiative through four phases in sequence. The
    structure is familiar; the discipline around it is what made the difference.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-12 grid md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
    {[
      {
        n: '01',
        name: 'Discover',
        desc: 'Problem framing with the cross-functional triad in the room from the start. Customer research, technical context, design exploration. Exit: a signed problem brief.',
      },
      {
        n: '02',
        name: 'Plan',
        desc: 'Paired problem brief and technical solution brief. Defined success metrics. Dashboard plan committed before Build. Post-launch review cadence scheduled.',
      },
      {
        n: '03',
        name: 'Build',
        desc: 'SDLC runs inside this phase. Design active in hi-fi and QA, not handed off at ticket creation. Customer partners engaged on significant initiatives.',
      },
      {
        n: '04',
        name: 'Measure',
        desc: 'Structured post-launch reviews against the metrics defined at Plan. Triad reconvenes. Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decision documented. Loop back to Discover.',
      },
    ].map((phase) => (
      <div class="p-6 border border-ink/15 bg-cream-warm/50">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">{phase.n}</p>
        <p class="font-display text-2xl text-ink mb-3">{phase.name}<span class="text-orange">.</span></p>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft leading-snug">{phase.desc}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <p>
    Design and customer proximity run through all four phases as standing threads, not as
    one-time gates. Design is never "started" at ticket assignment. Customer contact is a
    calendar commitment with defined minimums per phase. The PDLC governs initiative-level
    work; SDLC runs inside Build. Iteration on existing features routes back through
    Measure and Discover, not straight back to Build.
  </p>

  <h2>The three non-negotiables</h2>

  <p>
    The framework introduced a lot. To make it real instead of aspirational, I named three
    things as non-negotiable from day one.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The triad engages from Discover, not from Plan.</strong> Technical feasibility
    and design implications shape the problem brief itself. Loops back from Measure
    re-engage the triad before returning to Build. This is the single change that did the
    most to fix Define as a black hole.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Measurement is the spine.</strong> Every initiative entering Plan has defined
    success metrics, a dashboard plan, and a post-launch review scheduled. Dashboards
    exist at launch. Analytics is engaged at Plan, not at launch.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decisions happen on a defined cadence,
    documented, with feed-forward to Discover.</strong> Every significant initiative gets
    a formal decision. Features without decisions don't accumulate silently into
    maintenance burden.
  </p>

  <h2>DACI as the ownership model</h2>

  <p>
    For each phase, I defined who is the Driver, Approver, Contributor, and Informed. The
    pattern adapts at the team level (each team revisits its charter with KPIs, personas,
    target users, and team-specific DACI), but the overall structure is fixed. The
    discipline of named ownership at each gate is what turned the framework from a process
    document into a working operating model.
  </p>

  <h2>The structural commitments</h2>

  <p>
    A framework is only as strong as the infrastructure supporting it. Alongside the PDLC
    rollout, I named four parallel commitments leadership had to make for the operating
    model to actually work.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>A single source of truth for specs.</strong> Designate one system as
    authoritative. Migration-forward policy. New initiatives use it from day one.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>A functioning deprecation process.</strong> Quarterly feature health reviews.
    Defined approval path for Reinvest, Maintain, or Deprecate decisions. Customer notice,
    migration path, and sunset date for every deprecation. Without this, AI-accelerated
    build would only compound the maintenance burden.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Research access infrastructure.</strong> Weekly customer touchpoint cadence as
    a calendar commitment, not a best practice. Named research coordinator per team. A
    searchable, accessible repository of insights for the whole product organization.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>A standing health review.</strong> A regular leadership forum on whether gates
    are being respected, measurement is happening, teams are stuck, and friction is
    surfacing. Not a status meeting. The mechanism that keeps the framework from
    ossifying.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this case study</h2>

  <p>
    Operating model design is the work most design leaders never get to do, and the work
    that most differentiates a Sr. Director from a VP. It's not about choosing a process
    framework. It's about diagnosing the structural reason a company keeps shipping things
    it can't measure, designing the cross-functional architecture that fixes it, and
    getting product, engineering, and PMM to actually adopt it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Design upstream into discovery. Measurement as the spine. The loop closed by a real
    decision. That's the leverage.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
